  'trading-strategies-guide',
  '100 Trading Strategies: The Complete Guide for Every Market',
  'From beginner-friendly buy-and-hold approaches to advanced algorithmic systems—discover proven trading strategies used by professional traders worldwide.',
  E'# 100 Trading Strategies: The Complete Guide for Every Market\n\nFrom beginner-friendly buy-and-hold approaches to advanced algorithmic systems—discover proven trading strategies used by professional traders worldwide, complete with entry/exit rules and risk management guidelines.\n\n## Why Learn Multiple Trading Strategies?\n\nMarkets are dynamic—what works in a trending bull market may fail in a sideways range. Professional traders maintain a toolkit of strategies, selecting the right approach for current market conditions. This comprehensive guide covers 100 strategies across all major categories.\n\n---\n\n## Time-Based Trading Strategies\n\nThese strategies are defined primarily by how long you hold positions.\n\n### 1. Buy and Hold Strategy\n**Level:** Beginner | **Timeframe:** Years to decades | **Frequency:** 1–5 trades/year\n\nA long-term investment approach where assets are purchased and held regardless of short-term fluctuations.\n\n**Entry:** Buy fundamentally strong assets at fair or undervalued prices.\n**Exit:** Rarely exit. Only sell when fundamentals deteriorate significantly.\n**Notable Traders:** Warren Buffett, Charlie Munger, John Bogle\n\n### 2. Swing Trading\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Days to weeks | **Frequency:** 5–20 trades/month\n\nA medium-term strategy that seeks to capture price movements over several days to weeks.\n\n**Entry:** Buy at swing lows in uptrends, short at swing highs in downtrends.\n**Exit:** Target the opposite end of the swing range. Trail stops as position moves.\n**Notable Traders:** Paul Tudor Jones\n\n### 3. Day Trading\n**Level:** Advanced | **Timeframe:** Minutes to hours | **Frequency:** 5–100 trades/day\n\nPositions are opened and closed within the same trading day to avoid overnight risk.\n\n**Entry:** Look for setups in the first 1-2 hours of market open.\n**Exit:** All positions closed before market close.\n**Notable Traders:** Ross Cameron, Andrew Aziz\n\n### 4. Scalping\n**Level:** Expert | **Timeframe:** Seconds to minutes | **Frequency:** 10–200 trades/day\n\nUltra-short-term strategy aiming to profit from small price movements.\n\n**Entry:** Enter on minor pullbacks using 1-minute charts.\n**Exit:** Target 0.1%-0.5% per trade.\n\n---\n\n## Trend Following Strategies\n\n"The trend is your friend"—these strategies capitalize on established market momentum.\n\n### 5. Classic Trend Following\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Weeks to months\n\nFollow established trends until a clear reversal signal appears.\n\n**Entry:** Enter when price breaks above 20-day high (long) or below 20-day low (short).\n**Exit:** Trail stop using 10-day low (for longs) or 10-day high (for shorts).\n**Notable Traders:** Ed Seykota, Richard Dennis (Turtle Traders)\n\n### 6. Breakout Trading\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Intraday to multi-day\n\nEnter trades when price breaks out of support or resistance levels.\n\n**Entry:** Enter on close above resistance with volume surge (50%+ above average).\n**Exit:** Target measured move from breakout point.\n**Notable Traders:** Jesse Livermore\n\n### 7. Momentum Trading\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Days to weeks\n\nBuy assets showing strong upward momentum, sell those showing downward momentum.\n\n### 8. Moving Average Crossover\n**Level:** Beginner | **Timeframe:** Weeks to months\n\nUse moving average crossovers (e.g., 50/200 SMA) to identify trend changes.\n\n### 9. Donchian Channel\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Weeks to months\n\nThe original Turtle Trading system using price channel breakouts.\n\n### 10. Parabolic SAR\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Intraday to weekly\n\nUse trailing dots above/below price to identify trend direction and reversals.\n\n### 11. ADX Trend Trading\n**Level:** Intermediate | **Timeframe:** Daily\n\nUse the Average Directional Index to measure trend strength before entering.\n\n### 12. Supertrend Strategy\n**Level:** Beginner | **Timeframe:** Daily to weekly\n\nA simplified trend-following indicator combining ATR with price action.\n\n---\n\n## Technical Indicator Strategies\n\nStrategies built around specific technical indicators for precise entry/exit timing.\n\n### 13. RSI Divergence\nTrade divergences between RSI and price for reversal signals.\n\n### 14. MACD Histogram\nUse MACD histogram changes for momentum shifts.\n\n### 15. Bollinger Band Squeeze\nTrade volatility expansions after Bollinger Band contractions.\n\n### 16. Stochastic Oscillator\nUse %K/%D crossovers in overbought/oversold zones.\n\n### 17. Ichimoku Cloud\nComprehensive system using cloud, tenkan/kijun lines for trend and support.\n\n### 18. CCI (Commodity Channel Index)\nIdentify cyclical trends using CCI extremes.\n\n### 19. Williams %R\nSimilar to stochastic but inverted scale for momentum.\n\n### 20. On-Balance Volume\nUse cumulative volume to confirm price trends.\n\n### 21. VWAP Trading\nUse Volume Weighted Average Price for intraday mean reversion.\n\n### 22. Keltner Channel\nSimilar to Bollinger but uses ATR instead of standard deviation.\n\n### 23–28. Additional Indicators\nMFI, Chaikin Oscillator, Elder Ray, Force Index, Trix, Ultimate Oscillator.\n\n---\n\n## Chart Pattern Strategies\n\nStrategies based on recognizable price formations.\n\n### 29. Head and Shoulders\nClassic reversal pattern with three peaks.\n\n### 30. Double Top/Bottom\nTwo-peak/trough reversal patterns.\n\n### 31. Triangle Breakouts\nAscending, descending, and symmetrical triangle patterns.\n\n### 32. Cup and Handle\nBullish continuation pattern common in growth stocks.\n\n### 33. Flags and Pennants\nShort-term continuation patterns with 80%+ success rates.\n\n### 34. Wedge Patterns\nRising and falling wedge reversal patterns.\n\n### 35. Rectangle Consolidation\nRange-bound trading before breakout.\n\n### 36–40. Advanced Patterns\nDiamond, Broadening Formation, Bump and Run, Channel Trading, Harmonic Patterns.\n\n---\n\n## Advanced Trading Methods\n\nSophisticated strategies for experienced traders.\n\n### 41. Mean Reversion\nTrade the tendency of prices to revert to their average.\n\n### 42. Statistical Arbitrage\nExploit temporary pricing inefficiencies between correlated assets.\n\n### 43. Pairs Trading\nSimultaneously long/short correlated assets.\n\n### 44. Market Making\nProvide liquidity by quoting both buy and sell prices.\n\n### 45. Volatility Trading\nTrade volatility itself rather than direction.\n\n### 46. Gap Trading\nTrade opening gaps based on overnight news.\n\n### 47. Sector Rotation\nRotate capital between sectors based on economic cycles.\n\n### 48. Intermarket Analysis\nAnalyze relationships between stocks, bonds, commodities, currencies.\n\n### 49. Seasonal Trading\nExploit recurring calendar-based patterns.\n\n### 50. Dark Pool Analysis\nTrack institutional order flow for edge.\n\n### 51–55. More Advanced\nEvent-driven, merger arbitrage, short selling, contrarian trading, sentiment analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Management Strategies\n\n### 56. Fixed Fractional Position Sizing\nRisk a fixed percentage of capital per trade.\n\n### 57. Kelly Criterion\nMathematically optimal position sizing based on edge.\n\n### 58. Anti-Martingale\nIncrease position size after wins, decrease after losses.\n\n### 59. Portfolio Hedging\nUse options or inverse ETFs to protect positions.\n\n### 60. Correlation Management\nDiversify across uncorrelated assets.\n\n### 61. ATR-Based Stops\nUse Average True Range for volatility-adjusted stop losses.\n\n---\n\n## Options Strategies\n\n### 62. Covered Calls\nSell calls against stock holdings for income.\n\n### 63. Protective Puts\nBuy puts to insure portfolio positions.\n\n### 64. Iron Condor\nSell OTM put and call spreads for range-bound markets.\n\n### 65. Butterfly Spread\nPrecision strike trading for specific price targets.\n\n### 66. Straddle/Strangle\nProfit from large moves in either direction.\n\n### 67. Delta Neutral\nDirection-free options trading.\n\n---\n\n## Algorithmic Trading Strategies\n\n### 68. Moving Average Crossover Algo\nAutomated trend following using MA crossovers.\n\n### 69. Mean Reversion Algo\nAutomated mean reversion with statistical triggers.\n\n### 70. Machine Learning Models\nML-powered pattern recognition and prediction.\n\n### 71. High-Frequency Trading\nUltra-fast execution exploiting micro-inefficiencies.\n\n### 72. Grid Trading\nPlace orders at regular intervals above and below price.\n\n### 73–77. More Algos\nTWAP, VWAP execution, arbitrage bots, sentiment bots, order flow algos.\n\n---\n\n## Crypto-Specific Strategies\n\n### 78. Crypto Arbitrage\nExploit price differences across exchanges.\n\n### 79. DeFi Yield Farming\nEarn yield from decentralized finance protocols.\n\n### 80. NFT Flipping\nBuy and sell NFTs for profit.\n\n---\n\n## Commodity Strategies\n\n### 81. Contango/Backwardation\nTrade futures curve structure.\n\n### 82. Spread Trading\nTrade price differences between related commodities.\n\n---\n\n## Forex Strategies\n\n### 83. Carry Trade\nProfit from interest rate differentials between currencies.\n\n### 84. News Trading\nTrade economic data releases and central bank decisions.\n\n---\n\n## Additional Strategies (85–100)\n\n85. Dollar-Cost Averaging\n86. Value Investing\n87. Growth Investing\n88. Dividend Investing\n89. Index Fund Investing\n90. Thematic Investing\n91. ESG Investing\n92. Turnaround Trading\n93. IPO Trading\n94. SPAC Trading\n95. Earnings Play Trading\n96. Pre-Market Trading\n97. After-Hours Trading\n98. Penny Stock Trading\n99. Biotech Catalyst Trading\n100. Macro Trading\n\n---\n\n## Choosing the Right Strategy\n\nThe best strategy depends on your:\n- **Time commitment:** Full-time traders can scalp; part-time traders suit swing trading\n- **Risk tolerance:** Conservative investors prefer buy-and-hold; aggressive traders may scalp\n- **Capital:** Some strategies require significant capital (options, futures)\n- **Market conditions:** Trend-following works in trending markets; mean reversion in ranges\n\nStart with one strategy, master it, then gradually expand your toolkit.',
  'Trading Strategies',
